attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, stripped

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: DNS Query To Remote Access Software Domain From Non-Browser App
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
An adversary may use legitimate desktop support and remote access software, such as Team Viewer, Go2Assist, LogMein, AmmyyAdmin, etc, to establish an interactive command and control channel to target systems within networks.
These services are commonly used as legitimate technical support software, and may be allowed by application control within a target environment.
Remote access tools like VNC, Ammyy, and Teamviewer are used frequently when compared with other legitimate software commonly used by adversaries. (Citation: Symantec Living off the Land)

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered hacktool. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary is a statically linked version of tmate, a legitimate terminal sharing application. It contains numerous strings indicating its identity, such as "tmate -S /tmp/tmate.sock new-session -d" and configuration paths like "%s/.tmate.conf". Its functionality involves extensive use of SSH and cryptography (evidenced by libssh and OpenSSL strings) for secure remote sessions, filesystem access for configuration and keys (e.g., `~/.ssh/id_rsa`, `/etc/ssh/ssh_config`), and shell execution (`/bin/sh`) as part of its core, expected behavior.
